               <note xml:id="d2e32979" n="44"> Appears only in BT,
                                here and in bHul 27b (and also in
                                bQid71a, but not in the
                                Vilna print, where his name has been skipped), but I assume he is
                                Palestinian because he is always designated רבי, see Introduction
                                5.1.3.2.2, because in bPes 114a he is
                                designated דאגדתא (he who transmits aggadah, see Introduction
                                5.1.3.2.6) and in bQid 71 he is described
                                within the context of the Palestinian study house. Hyman, Toldoth, 782-4 argues that he is the person
                                designated simply Isaac (5) in PT, but he has no proof for this, and
                                Isaac (5) is probably Ahi (7)’s son.</note>
               <note xml:id="d2e33008" n="45">
                                Mentioned with no chronological context, see Introduction
                            7.4.4.</note>
